title: For Sale:  Shilen DGV Target / Varminter, Stiller Action
postcontent: This is a barely used / like new, semi-custom Shilen DGV varminter in 223 Rem.  These are not very common as Shilen only recently (last few years) re-started producing and putting out full rifles like they used to do a couple decades back.  This example is a Shilen select match stainless steel barrel, mated to a Stiller Predator action which has been branded under the Shilen name as DGV ("damn good varminter" is what I'm told the initials represent)  The barrel is 24 inches long from end of action to muzzle, and tapers to a heavy 1 inch final diameter at the muzzle. It has  a 1:9 twist, and is fitted with their Shilen competition trigger which I have set at 6 ounces.  It rides on a separately acquired Mcmillan Tooley MBR flat bottomed stock (Shilen doesn't sell that stock, I had to get that from Mcmillan).  The entire rig with scope and Seekins Precision rings weighs in at 15 pounds.  I've had this rig for about a year/ year and a half, and have shot it only maybe 5 or 6 times, and so it's barely past the official break-in period (I've got maybe 200-220 rounds thru it, that's it.)  As with all my toys, it has been very well kept and never mishandled, abused, dropped etc, .  It's very pleasant to shoot (low recoiling 223 on a fairly heavy 15 pound platform), and groups around 1/2 MOA, some ammo better, some worse. THE REASON I'M SELLING IS THIS :  When I ordered this Shilen rig, this rifle was intended to be a replacement for another 223 target / varminter I have, for which I'm running out of my supply of ammo that it shoots best, and that ammo (PMC 52 grain HPBT Match)  has been discontinued for years, and cant be found anywhere anymore. (Believe me, I've spent hours on the internet trying to find that ammo, and even spoke to PMC themselves. ) That other rig, which I've had for 15 years, is an accurized  223 Rem 700, with a straight taper 1.25 inch HS Precision 1:12 twist barrel, which shoots that particular PMC factory match 52 grain load into 1/4 inch ragged one hole groups (and better), all day, every day, hot or cold, clean or dirty. But I'm running out of that ammo, and have only 12 boxes left, probably the last 12 boxes on the planet, which is  barely enough to go target shooting once a month for a year, and then I'm totally out forever. This Shilen with the faster 1:9 twist, was supposed to give me more options for shooting heavier and more readily available 69 grain factory match bullets, as I do not handload, and so I am stuck shooting factory match offerings, of which there are many, many different ones in the 68/69 grain range. So I had figured I would be able to find one that shoots 69 grainers as well as my other rig shoots the 52's I am running out of.  Well, so irony of ironies, wouldn't ya know it, but this Shilen ALSO loves that defunct PMC 52 grain factory match load, even though this is a faster twist gun designed primarily for bullets up to 69 grains.  So it will group Federal Match 69 grainers at 1/2 MOA (still excellent), but will actually shoot those old PMC 52 grain match loads into 1/4 inch groups @ 100 yards.  Can ya believe the irony for me?  So bottom line, this is an excellent rifle for any competent handloader who can tune a proper load for it.  If I can get 1/4 inch groups out of that old PMC ammo, and 1/2 inch groups from current production federal 69 grain factory match ammo, then obviously the rifle has amazing potential for those who handload.  Unfortunately I do not handload, so acquiring this rifle did nothing for me, nor did it accomplish the purpose for which I got it, so I would rather get some money out of it and move onto a new build.  Components cost for me, excluding shipping and taxes on this rig, was this.  Shilen DGV Barreled action (select stainless barrel on Stiller Predator action) was $1500.  The Mcmillan Tooley MBR stock was another 535, .  Seekins Precision rings 135.  Shilen Competition trigger 200.  So I've got about 2370-2400 in the gun, excluding scope, excluding shipping and taxes. I think a fair deal for somebody would be 1700 including rings, 1600 if you don't want the rings.  I take a bath for about 700/800 bucks, but get to move on to another build, and you get an excellent, nearly new, barely shot rig for about a 700/800 dollar discount, and don't have to wait months to build one

Maybe someone one that has experience working on ak47's can fix this easily or a gunsmith could probably fix it for cheap, it could be that the mag springs are worn out or buildup of the polymer coating from the ammo due to a hot chamber causing the extracted casing to slow down the bolt, I don't know.
